observations.recommendation:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to issue Demand Letters to beneficiaries of the Special Employment Assistance for the payment of their loans and to the existing cooperatives to settle immediately their loans, which are already due;

Require the Municipal Accountant to submit the necessary documents for their request for authority to write-off the loans granted to various NGOs;

Require the employee still connected with the Municipality to settle his unliquidated cash advance for travel immediately, otherwise, deduct from his salaries the amount due;

Exhaust all possible remedies available to collect from persons liable who are separated or deceased, such as resorting to legal remedies, if necessary; and

Ensure that receivable accounts are properly monitored and appropriately acted upon so that these are immediately collected or settled when due.

We recommended that the Management:
Require the Inventory Committee to prepare and submit a Comprehensive Physical Inventory Plan and Inventory Count Form, as part of the documentation for the one-time cleansing conducted;
Require the Inventory Committee to assign new property number and tag new property stickers to the PPE items, in view of the coding convention provided in Item 5.7 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31 2020;
Require the Property Custodian to renew all Property Acknowledgment Receipts and ensure that they are signed by each accountable individual; and
Require the Inventory Committee to submit to the Audit Team the complete documentation of the one-time cleansing conducted, in compliance with the said Circular.

Thru the Inventory Committee, conduct physical inventory of all items of PPE of the Municipality, whether acquired through purchase or donation, including those constructed by administration and found at station, taking into consideration the capitalization threshold of P15,000.00, in accordance with the procedures prescribed under COA Circular No.  2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;

Update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile the same with accounting records to make the records reflective of the actual count of PPEs;

Instruct the General Services Officer to cancel the Property Acknowledgement Receipts of the properties below the capitalization threshold and issue Inventory Custodian Slips in lieu thereof;

Undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and

Direct the GSO to prepare, maintain and update Property Cards for each item of the PPE pursuant to Section 114, Paragraph 4 of the MNGAs for LGUs, Volume I.

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to reverse the journal entries made to drop the 326 PPE items, with a net book value of P25,935,191.35, and derecognize properties only upon the grant of specific authority by the COA and based on properly accomplished IIRUP, WMR or PTR, whichever is applicable, after the completion of disposal procedures;

Direct all the accountable officers who are in custody of unserviceable properties to return the same to the GSO for the institution of measures for the proper disposal of these properties in accordance with Title V of COA Circular No. 92-386 dated October 20, 1992;

Direct the GSO to issue demand letters signed by the Agency Head or his designated representative to accountable persons of non-existing or missing PPEs, requiring them to produce the PPE or request for relief from property accountability from COA; otherwise, require the Municipal Accountant to take up necessary accounting entries to recognize in the books of accounts the loss of PPE and, where appropriate, to set up the corresponding receivables from concerned accountable officers/personnel;

Instruct the Disposal Committee to institute measures for the proper disposition of missing, non-existing or unserviceable PPE items in accordance with pertinent provisions of COA Circular Nos. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, 92-386 dated October 20, 1992 and COA-DBM Joint Circular No. 2024-1 dated January 30, 2024;

For existing semi-expendable properties, instruct the GSO to issue Inventory Custodian Slips to the end-user and cancel the Property Acknowledgement Receipts to establish accountability; and

Strictly comply with the rules and regulations on the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts, supply and property management and disposal of government properties.

Adhere to the provision of Section 5 DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017 to ensure the optimal utilization of 20% Development Fund to help achieve the desirable socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes of the Municipality;

Submit justifications for the delay and non-implementation/completion of the above-mentioned priority projects aggregating P64.407 million from CYs 2020-2023; and 

Initiate corrective measures to fasttrack the implementation and completion of unimplemented and ongoing priority projects for CYs 2020-2023 in order to avoid accumulation of unimplemented projects and to ensure the optimal utilization of 20% Development Fund in the ensuing year at lower cost due to soaring prices of commodities.

