We recommended that Management instruct the BAC to:

Conduct bid evaluation procedure during the procurement process pursuant to Sections 32 and 34 of the RIRR to ensure award of contract to the responsive and eligible bidders;

Submit to the Audit Team copies of the approved Bidding Documents intended for sale to prospective bidders prepared in accordance with Section 17 of the RIRR;

Upload the Bidding Documents in the PhilGEPS as required in Section 17.4 of the RIRR to give interested bidders sufficient information about the procurement at hand;

Require the bidders to submit statements of their SLCC, as specified in the Bidding Documents, in compliance with Section 23 of the RIRR so as to ensure that the prospective bidder has the technical and financial capability to undertake the contract; and

Send invitations to representatives of duly recognized private group and non-government organization (NGO) to attend as observers in the procurement proceedings in compliance with Section 13 of the Revised Implement Rules and Regulations (RIRR) of Republic Act (RA) No. 9184.

We recommended that Management instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

a. Draw a journal entry voucher (JEV) to adjust the honoraria paid for the month of December 2018 amounting to P104,700.00 which was inadvertently recorded in books of the general fund instead of the trust fund;

b. Re-compute the proper amount of honoraria from January 2018 to June 2019 in accordance with the designation and corresponding rates for every member of the BAC and the allied committees/services as provided in Section 5.3 of DBM Budget Circular No. 2004-5A dated October 7, 2005 taking into consideration the regulation that the average monthly honoraria should not exceed the 25% of the recipients’ monthly basic salary as required in Section 5.4 of same circular. Support the claim with the corresponding Notices of Award to ensure that the honoraria would be based solely on successfully completed procurement projects;

c. Adjust proportionately the computed claims for honoraria, if the available trust fund arising from fees collected from contractors/suppliers amounting to P555,900.00 does not suffice pursuant to Section 3.5 of DBM Budget Circular No. 2004-5A dated October 7, 2005. Any honoraria paid in excess of what should have been distributed, should be refunded immediately by the recipients as the transaction constitutes an irregular disbursement having been incurred without complying with the allowable sources provided in DBM Budget Circular No. 2007-3 dated November 29, 2009. This is without prejudice to the issuance of a Notice of Disallowance pursuant to COA Circular No. 2009-006 dated September 15, 2009, if not refunded immediately; and

d. For all claims for honoraria of the BAC, adhere strictly to the provisions of DBM Budge5 Circular Nos. 2004-5A and 2007-3 dated October 7, 2005 and November 29, 2009, respectively.

