We recommended to management the following:

a.	Require the members of the SB to fully refund the amount of overpayment of P 276,750.00  that was not deducted from their RATA due to absences and non-conduct of the required four sessions in a month;

b.	Instruct the Municipal accounting Office to deduct from the RATA claims of the SB members pro-rated amounts based on actual work/attendance in regular sessions;

c.	Support claims for RATA with SB minutes of meetings and certification of attendance from the SB secretary;

d.	Strictly comply with the requirements of Section 52 of RA. No. 7160 on the conduct of at least one regular session a week.

We recommended the following:

1. Set simultaneous deadlines for submission of eligibility requirements/ documents and the bid proposal envelopes (“Class A’ and “Class B”) and;

2. Design appropriate controls to keep under utmost secrecy and confidentiality the number and identity/ies of prospective bidder/s buying bidding documents.

We recommended that the Municipality: 

1. 		Exert all legal/remedial measures to collect the long overdue obligation of the subject cooperative in the amount of P500,000.00 plus corresponding surcharge;

2. 	Require the subject cooperative to submit periodic performance and operations reports to determine whatever problems it encountered that resulted to the subject delinquency; 

3. 	Henceforth, re-evaluate the present MOA as to its relevance and effectiveness for similar transactions in the future to protect the best interest of the municipality in its goal to provide the essential services needed by its constituents;

4. 	Refrain from undertaking lending activities involving such big amounts as this is an exclusive function of government financial institutions such as the Land Bank of the Philippines and the Development Bank of the Philippines and limit itself to small amount lending activities like the Self Employment Assistance (SEA).
